maybe that happens after you get a faculty that's

07:59.703 --> 08:19.293
been established and they're moving along with 
their program and new faculty are coming in with

07:59.703 --> 08:19.293
new ideas and they want their kind of program, you 
know, to emerge and you begin to get kind of a clash

07:59.703 --> 08:19.293
here. I would describe it this way, probably the 
first 20 years it was department within a college

08:29.217 --> 08:36.929
and all of our effort was toward the students. The 
fragmented segment started when numbers of new

08:38.592 --> 08:52.373
faculty or faculty after a few years wanted 
specialization you know don't get me involved

08:52.572 --> 09:17.584
with those other people this is my field very 
narrow that's right and and of course they do good

08:52.572 --> 09:17.584
things you know if you're looking for 
specialization they have really specialized and

08:52.572 --> 09:17.584
can tell you the the finer things of whatever 
they've specialized in but There's a trade-off.

09:19.807 --> 09:29.841
When you go that deep into specialization, you 
lose track of what the overall mission and the

09:19.807 --> 09:29.841
overall picture is. And when we celebrated our 
30th College of Education 30th anniversary, I

09:30.141 --> 09:43.740
took the lead in writing up the history on the 
Department of Curriculum Instruction,

09:30.141 --> 09:43.740
Educational Curriculum Instruction. And when I 
finished, I finished with the words, quo vadis,

09:43.720 --> 09:50.427
wherefore goest thou? Because I think that's what 
happens. People begin to lose, what's the

09:53.550 --> 09:56.473
mission? What are the objectives? How do we work 
together to get there? And you get fragmented

10:01.498 --> 10:06.003
things going on. Now, I'm not going to ask you the 
negative. Who were your favorite colleagues? Oh,

10:11.277 --> 10:12.760
there were so many. Gosh. Short time that he was 
