years. I would say this first signs of fragmenting

12:12.135 --> 12:27.917
didn't come in until maybe... See, Bob Schutz was 
department head for ten years, and I would say only

12:12.135 --> 12:27.917
the last couple of years where all of us began to see 
it. But I'd say, you know, my time and seven, eight

12:28.522 --> 12:40.624
years under Bob's time, there was a very cohesive 
group. And as I say, the fragmented people, the

12:40.744 --> 12:49.359
people that I associated with that 
fragmentation, didn't want to do that. They

12:49.419 --> 12:50.361
weren't. interested in having lunch. I think they 
were more interested in pursuing their their own

12:53.234 --> 12:59.001
specialization or whatever, you know. I always 
worry if those people fall within what I call the

12:59.690 --> 13:05.495
missionary complex. By that I mean the person who 
feels that he or she is doing us a favor by being

13:07.117 --> 13:22.231
here, that they've come from a superior 
civilization, that we're behind the times, and

13:07.117 --> 13:22.231
they're going to be here doing missionary 
service, and then they will return and leave us

13:07.117 --> 13:22.231
peasants. And I always worry about that. I think 
there's some truth to that. Now, we've had a couple

13:26.555 --> 13:29.578
people like that who have kind of come in with that 
attitude and have left, but have come back. Oh,

13:35.187 --> 13:37.070
good, good, good. And said, this is where I want to 
be. But apparently, for whatever reason, they had

13:39.854 --> 13:44.621
to experience that. They had to go through this 
missionary approach and saying, you know, we're

13:44.821 --> 13:56.578
coming out of a program that's above you, et 
cetera, et cetera, and I'm going back there, only

13:44.821 --> 13:56.578
to find out that when they got back there, that 
wasn't. what it looked like when they had been a

13:57.824 --> 14:01.155
student or whatever. And now they wanted to come 
back. And they were leaving tenured positions

14:05.007 --> 14:10.585
elsewhere, pretty good positions, just to come 
back. Now you served how many years here? Thirty. I

14:16.308 --> 14:17.169
was here thirty years. Thirty years, exactly. Do 
you have any advice on this? I've just appointed

14:24.076 --> 14:25.877
you as the consultant. Do you have any advice for 
the College of Education today?

14:32.804 --> 14:40.892
I would really like to see them come back to 
spending more of a informal, camaraderie

14:41.682 --> 15:02.341
kind of building an atmosphere of cohesiveness 
again, like we had those first 15, 20 years, where

14:41.682 --> 15:02.341
we really did have a mission we understood and 
goals to be accomplished. And we're not afraid to

15:03.442 --> 15:08.247
be innovative and experimental, if you want to 
call it. Because I think in education today, we're

15:08.902 --> 15:16.176
kind of faltering all across the country. And what 
worked 20 years ago is still there. And that's not

15:23.870 --> 15:25.313
the case. Things have changed. I think there are 
some signs of spurts. Although I'm only getting it

15:32.392 --> 15:37.237
from the outside now because I've been away for 
three years. But I'm beginning to see signs where

15:37.357 --> 15:45.345
they're, for example, this whole thrust with the 
internet and technology. I'm seeing and hearing

15:46.647 --> 16:00.441
comments by people out of the College of Education 
that maybe they are locking into that and

15:46.647 --> 16:00.441
recognizing that this thing is going to be huge. 
and it's going to impact education at all levels. I

16:05.453 --> 16:06.499
don't care if it's pre-school years to doctoral 
program years. The internet and technology are

16:12.807 --> 16:19.456
going to just have a tremendous impact. And I think 
all the research and grantsmanship that's going

16:19.596 --> 16:28.609
on out there now to get into that ballpark. And 
they're having some success. They're hitting on

16:32.028 --> 16:37.055
